# Architectural Blueprint and AI Governance Strategy for AutoCompt via Google Antigravity

## Introduction to Agentic Governance in Software Ecosystems
The integration of autonomous coding assistants into complex, living enterprise codebases represents a profound paradigm shift in modern software engineering. As software systems evolve from repositories exclusively authored by human developers to dynamic environments co-authored by artificial intelligence, the necessity for rigorous architectural governance, explicitly defined constraints, and deterministic execution protocols becomes absolutely paramount. The "AutoCompt" ecosystem, a sophisticated Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) platform tailored specifically for the nuanced requirements of the Quebec real estate and property management market, presents a uniquely challenging environment for an autonomous AI agent. Constructed on a modern, highly interactive technology stack comprising React 19, TypeScript, Vite, Express, Firebase, and Gemini AI, the application is responsible for managing intricate financial logic, enforcing strict Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) matrices, maintaining precise visual identity guidelines, and ensuring stringent regional legal compliance regarding data privacy and property management statutes.

However, an inspection of the current architectural state of the AutoCompt repository reveals a critical structural vulnerability: the presence of a monolithic App.tsx file encompassing 23,573 lines of code. This single file houses an overwhelming majority of the core application logic, routing instructions, and state management protocols. During agentic augmentation, such a massive monolith poses a severe operational risk. When unconstrained, large language models and autonomous coding agents are highly susceptible to context loss, unauthorized and sweeping refactoring, and the destructive overwriting of functional, verified code. To completely mitigate these systemic risks, the deployment of Google Antigravity 2.0 requires a meticulously engineered set of persistent rules, specialized skills, and sequential workflows. Unlike traditional, single-threaded conversational coding assistants, Antigravity operates not as a simplistic chatbot, but as a persistent software organism capable of running multiple specialized agents in parallel, executing localized browser-based verification, and autonomously navigating complex directory structures to prove feature functionality. This inherent power requires equivalent restraint. This comprehensive research report provides an exhaustive strategy for encoding the AutoCompt Golden Rules, the non-negotiable UI/UX directives, and the critical legal compliance constraints into the Antigravity configuration matrix. By establishing explicit permission tiers, progressive knowledge disclosure, and directory-targeted behavioral triggers, the integrity of the AutoCompt ecosystem can be rigorously preserved while simultaneously leveraging the rapid iteration and problem-solving capabilities of an agent-first development environment.

## The Google Antigravity Structural Framework
To prevent an AI coding assistant from inadvertently deleting verified modules, corrupting established design patterns, or hallucinating incorrect tax logic, the governance model must move beyond reactive, prompt-based instructions into proactive, repository-level rule enforcement. Relying on a developer to manually remind the AI of the application's constraints during every interaction is inefficient and highly prone to error. Google Antigravity provides a sophisticated, tri-layered customization architecture designed specifically to address this challenge, consisting of Rules, Workflows, and Skills. Understanding the precise function and configuration of these three distinct layers is the foundational step in protecting and modernizing the AutoCompt codebase.

### The Tri-Layered Customization Architecture
The first layer of the Antigravity framework is composed of Rules, which function as contextual constraints. Rules act as the persistent foundational boundaries that continuously guide the agent's behavior at the foundational prompt level. They are stored as standard Markdown files within the .agents/rules/ directory of the active workspace and are strictly limited to 12,000 characters per file to ensure processing efficiency. Rules utilize a YAML frontmatter block at the beginning of the document to define their core metadata and, crucially, their execution triggers. This is where the non-negotiable dictates, such as the prohibition against deleting code or the requirement to use specific color palettes, are permanently encoded.

The second layer consists of Workflows, which define procedural sequences. While Rules provide continuous behavioral guidance, Workflows provide a structured, deterministic sequence of interconnected steps for the agent to follow. Stored as YAML or Markdown files within the .agents/workflows/ directory, these sequences are ideal for orchestrating complex, multi-stage operations that carry high risk, such as the systematic dismantling and refactoring of the massive App.tsx monolith, or the execution of automated deployment pipelines that require rigorous testing gates before completion.

The third layer comprises Skills, which represent modular capabilities designed to address the critical problem of context saturation. Indiscriminately loading an AI agent with entire codebases and hundreds of specialized tools leads to "Tool Bloat," resulting in high latency, financial waste, and "context rot," where the model becomes confused by an overwhelming volume of irrelevant data. Instead of forcing the model to memorize every technical requirement—such as the specific computational formatting of a complex Quebec tax form—Skills package this procedural knowledge into modular units located in the .agents/skills/ directory. Through a process of progressive disclosure, the agent is initially exposed only to a lightweight menu of metadata. It loads the heavy procedural instructions and scripts only when the user's explicit intent matches the skill's YAML description.

### Deterministic Rule Activation Protocols
For a financial and legally binding application like AutoCompt, the application of rules by the AI agent must be absolute and deterministic. Antigravity supports four primary activation types defined within the YAML frontmatter of the rule files, allowing developers to precisely target when and how constraints are applied.

The Always On protocol (alwaysApply: true or trigger: always_on) mandates that the rule is injected into the agent's context window for every single interaction, regardless of the task. This protocol is mandatory for AutoCompt's designated Golden Rules, ensuring they cannot be bypassed under any circumstances. The Glob Pattern protocol (match: "pattern") provides targeted activation, triggering the rule only when the agent explores or manipulates files that match a specific directory pattern (e.g., src/components/**/*.tsx). This mechanism is highly effective for enforcing the specific UI/UX design directives without cluttering the agent's context when it is working on backend server logic. The Model Decision protocol relies on the agent using natural language reasoning to determine if the rule is relevant to the current task. While flexible, this activation type should be strictly avoided for critical security and architectural rules within AutoCompt, as it introduces probabilistic variation into what must be deterministic constraints. Finally, the Manual protocol ensures a rule remains entirely dormant until explicitly invoked by the developer via an @ mention in the prompt interface.

## Encoding the AutoCompt Golden Rules
The project directives establish three fundamental "Golden Rules" that dictate the structural integrity of the AutoCompt platform. To guarantee that the Antigravity AI agent respects these boundaries implicitly, these rules must be translated into machine-readable constraints and encoded as Always On global rules utilizing explicit permission tiers. This configuration strategy divides the agent's potential actions into three distinct categories: operations that are allowed autonomously without human intervention, operations requiring explicit human confirmation before execution, and operations that are strictly forbidden under any context.

### Translating Rule 1: The Zero Deletion Policy
The first directive states: "Never delete existing UI modules. Hide them using conditional rendering based on the active profile, but never remove the underlying code (e.g., never delete Syndicat modules when working on Prospecteur)." This rule directly addresses one of the most common and catastrophic failure modes of autonomous AI assistants: the tendency to "nuke" functional, working code when attempting to optimize logic or respond to a narrow prompt. When human developers request a small change, AI assistants frequently lose track of the broader application context, overwriting essential instructions or interpreting a requested modification as a complete replacement rather than an addition.

To enforce this absolute boundary, an AGENTS.md file (or a specialized rule file located at .agents/rules/01-golden-rules.md) must be established with the highest priority configuration. The YAML frontmatter must dictate continuous, workspace-wide application across the entire React ecosystem. The body of the rule must explicitly define the "Never" tier : The agent is absolutely forbidden from utilizing terminal commands such as rm, unlink, or executing Git commands that result in the permanent deletion of any file located within the src/components/ directory.

Furthermore, the rule must not simply forbid action; it must explicitly dictate the required architectural pattern for module management. The agent must be instructed to utilize the existing rbacConfig.ts matrix to conditionally render views. For example, the agent must write logic such as if (!hasAccess(activeProfile, 'Syndicat')) return null; rather than excising the logic entirely. By embedding this operational philosophy directly into the persistent system instructions, the agent's continuous semantic compaction process will inherently reject any proposed operations or execution paths that involve file deletion, preserving the integrity of the 75% complete codebase.

### Translating Rules 2 and 3: Database Authority and Universal Modules
Rule 2 specifies that Google Drive functions as the core database for all file storage, mandating that all modules rely on the existing workspace integration and that data is strictly separated by Company/Building hierarchies. Rule 3 mandates the concept of Universal Modules, dictating that the Scanner IA (Factures), Dossiers Fiscaux, Sofi AI Assistant, and the Settings Gear must exist and remain accessible for all five user profiles.

Enforcing these rules requires the configuration to construct a robust "defense in depth" strategy. To satisfy Rule 2, the Antigravity agent must be provided with an instruction that permanently forbids the replacement of the Google Drive integration with alternative file storage mechanisms. For instance, the agent might autonomously decide that direct Firebase Storage bucket uploads are more efficient for a new module. The rule must preemptively block this reasoning, dictating that any module manipulating, uploading, or retrieving files must import and interface exclusively with the established driveService.ts utility.

To satisfy Rule 3 regarding Universal Modules, the rule must ensure that any automated refactoring of the Sidebar or Main Navigation components includes hardcoded guarantees. The agent must be instructed that the components rendering these four specific modules are invariant; they must remain unconditionally rendered in the layout wrapper, completely bypassing standard RBAC filtering arrays if necessary, ensuring that no profile update or permission tweak accidentally hides the core AI or settings functionality.

## Navigating and Enforcing the RBAC Matrix
The AutoCompt system currently relies on a sophisticated and explicit access matrix defined within src/lib/rbacConfig.ts, which governs the permissions and module visibility for five distinct professional profiles. The primary danger during agent-led development is the unintentional exposure of restricted modules to incorrect user profiles, or the failure to implement the required conditional logic within newly generated features. To completely mitigate this risk, the Antigravity configuration must enforce a mandatory verification loop. A rule must be defined stating that before the agent implements any new React view or modifies the navigation sidebar, it must first execute an automated read of the rbacConfig.ts file to verify its current state against the proposed changes.

### Profile-Specific Directives and Constraints
The rule matrix must explicitly define the expected logic and operational focus for each of the five profiles to guide the AI agent during feature implementation and UI generation:

| Profile | Application Focus | Permitted Modules & Agent Directives |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Prospecteur Immobilier** | Speed, mobility, fast invoicing in the field. | Modules: Scanner IA, Kilométrage GPS, Facturation, Bureau à domicile, Contrats & Résolutions, Sous-traitants, Déclaration TPS/TVQ, Conciliation bancaire, Taxes & Assurances, Tenue de livres. Directive: Strict enforcement of the $30,000 TPS/TVQ registration lock. |
| **Investisseur Immobilier** | Asset tracking, multi-tenant transparency. | Directive: Implement branching UI logic based on onboarding filter. If "Gestion déléguée", enforce Oversight Mode. If "Autogestion", enable Tenue de livres and the 100% strictly validated Répartition Fiscale engine. |
| **Flippeur Immobilier** | Budget control, fast property flips, contractors. | Modules: Includes DocuLegal and Heures & Paie. Directive: Restrict Heures & Paie strictly to manual entry interfaces; prohibit the agent from generating external payroll API integrations. |
| **Gestionnaire Immobilier** | Multi-tenant architecture, property administration. | Directive: Enforce multi-tier Google Drive folder structure mapping (Client -> Sub-folder Property 1 -> Tenue de livres). Require 1-click sharing functionality for financial ledgers. |
| **Syndicat de Copropriété** | Co-owner transparency, legal compliance. | Modules: Gestion des Cotisations, Tableau de Transparence, Loi 16 & Carnet d'entretien, SyndicAI. Directive: Prioritize immutable ledger creation for all compliance modules. |

A deeper analysis of these profiles reveals complex dependencies that the AI agent must be programmed to handle. For the Prospecteur Immobilier, the directive states that the Déclaration TPS/TVQ module must include a visual tracker alerting the user at $27,000 and locking compliance at $30,000. This is not arbitrary; the $30,000 threshold represents the exact point under Quebec law where a business loses "small supplier" status and is legally mandated to register for GST/QST. The agent must be instructed that this tracker cannot merely look at a single invoice. The logic generated must establish a Firebase listener that aggregates the total worldwide taxable supplies (including any associated entities) across a given calendar quarter and the four preceding quarters. The agent must write strict validation logic preventing further invoice generation without a registered tax number once the threshold is breached.

For the Investisseur Immobilier, the agent must recognize the internal state split within the profile. It must programmatically verify the onboarding filter state within the user's Firebase document. If Gestion déléguée is active, the UI must route exclusively to the Oversight Mode. If Autogestion is active, the UI must render the operational modules, including the explicitly read-only Tableau de Transparence. Crucially, when the agent develops the Répartition Fiscale engine, the rule must mandate an invariant mathematical check in the frontend form and backend validation: the distribution of fiscal responsibility among co-owners must add up to exactly 100%, rejecting any state change that calculates to 99.9% or 100.1%.

For the Gestionnaire Immobilier, the agent must strictly adhere to a multi-tenant folder architecture when manipulating the driveService.ts. The AI cannot be allowed to dump all client files into a single repository; it must procedurally generate and verify the existence of the Client -> Sub-folder Property 1 -> Tenue de livres hierarchy via Google Drive API calls before uploading any financial documents.

### Expansion of the Super Admin Panel Metrics
The existing SuperAdminPanel.tsx is functional but requires significant expansion based on the user's explicit metrics requirements. An Antigravity workflow can be structured to safely enhance this critical administrative interface without exposing sensitive backend routes. The agent must be instructed via the workflow to aggregate real-time API Token usage per profile, compile a comprehensive Client Directory encompassing emails, phone numbers, and active profiles, track the total volume of Legal Documents generated, and meticulously manage Beta Phase metrics. This Beta Phase tracking must include logic to parse the database for free month status expiration dates, survey completion flags, and suggested pricing data inputted by early adopters. The workflow must ensure that the agent establishes safe, read-only queries to the Firebase backend when constructing these administrative dashboards, preventing any accidental mutation of core user data during the aggregation process.

## Strict UI/UX Directives and The SOFI Entity Configuration
AutoCompt relies on a meticulously defined visual hierarchy, demanding absolute adherence to ensure user trust within a professional financial and real estate environment. The core directives specify rigid iconography styles, a highly specific global dark mode color palette, dynamic glassmorphism mechanics, and strict anatomical rules for the visualization of the "SOFI" AI entity. AI assistants, when tasked with creating new UI components, frequently attempt to "improve" designs by introducing unauthorized gradients, altering border radii, or utilizing unapproved color variables. This creative liberty must be strictly prohibited through targeted Glob rules.

### The Core Styling and Iconography Rules
A dedicated rule file (e.g., .agents/rules/02-ui-ux-directives.md) must be instantiated within the workspace. This rule must utilize a Glob pattern match: `**/*.tsx` to ensure it triggers whenever a React component is analyzed, modified, or created. The primary instruction must categorically forbid the use of solid or filled icons across the entire platform. The agent must be constrained to utilize strictly linear, outline-style iconography, maintaining a clean, wireframe aesthetic. The rule must explicitly state: "NO filled areas, NO solid glyphs, and NO gradients within shapes are permitted for any SVG or icon library import."

Furthermore, the global color palette instructions must be explicitly defined using precise Tailwind utility class formats, matching the existing codebase standards. The agent must be instructed that the use of pure black (#000000 or bg-black) for main backgrounds is strictly forbidden; the main body background across the application is exclusively Deep midnight blue (#0b1121).

### The Dual-Mode Reactive Glassmorphism Constraint (Dynamic Neon Beam)
The master design rules mandate a highly specific, three-layer DOM architecture for all module cards when the application is in Dark Mode. This architecture utilizes an interactive, rotating neon beam effect that must map **deterministically** to the active profile or module category token to preserve context-aware brand consistency.

The Antigravity rule must enforce the exact Document Object Model (DOM) structure and Tailwind/CSS composition required for these cards:
1. **Layer 1 (The External Wrapper):** The outermost container must use the Tailwind classes `p-[1px]`, `overflow-hidden`, and a dark background `bg-black/20` to act as the strict bounding container for the underlying light effect.
2. **Layer 2 (The Dynamic Neon Beam):** Centered inside the wrapper and sized at `250%`, this layer must utilize a pure transparent `conic-gradient` to create a faded tail effect. Crucially, the rule mandates the inclusion of the continuous rotation animation defined in the CSS as `spin-neon 5s linear infinite`.
3. **Layer 3 (The Inner Glass Core):** This layer must sit on top with a higher z-index (`z-10`). It must use the specific glassmorphism background class `bg-[#121b2d]/90` to obscure the center of the conic gradient. This exact layer composition forces the light to "spill" exclusively out of the 1-pixel border beneath it.

#### Chromatic Token Mapping Matrix for Profiles and Dashboard Modules:
The AI agent must never randomize or hardcode the beam's color variable, nor the accent borders. It must inject the color dynamically through a computed property or context based on the system state, matching these strict specifications:

| Profile / Target View Token | Module Context | Color Identity | Hex / Tailwind Accent Code |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `PROSPECTEUR IMMOBILIER` | `TABLEAU DE BORD`, `FACTURATION` | Emerald Green / Tech | `#10B981` / `from-emerald-500` |
| `INVESTISSEUR IMMOBILIER` | `GESTION IMMOBILIÈRE`, `CONCILIATION BANCAIRE`, `PLEX` | Cyan / Turquoise | `#06B6D4` / `from-cyan-500` |
| `FLIPPEUR IMMOBILIER` | `BUREAU À DOMICILE`, `RENOVATION` | Amber / Warm Gold | `#F59E0B` / `from-amber-500` |
| `GENRE / SYNDICAT DE COPROPRIÉTÉ` | `GESTION COTISATIONS`, `MURO`, `LOI16` | Purple / Indigo | `#8B5CF6` / `from-purple-500` |
| **`SOFI AI ASSISTANT CARD`** | Universal AI Interface (*Protected*) | Neon Purple | `#b535ff` / `from-[#b535ff]` |
| *Specific Cards* | `TENUE DE LIVRES` | Royal Blue | `#3B82F6` / `from-blue-500` |
| *Specific Cards* | `DÉCLARATION TPS / TVQ` | Magenta / Pink | `#EC4899` / `from-pink-500` |
| *Specific Cards* | `DOCULEGAL` | Clinical Indigo | `#6366F1` / `from-indigo-500` |
| *Specific Cards* | `HEURES & PAIE` | Teal | `#14B8A6` / `from-teal-500` |
| *Specific Cards* | `TAXES & ASSURANCES` | Secure Green | `#16A34A` / `from-green-600` |

#### Light Mode Fallback Enforcement:
Crucially, the rule contains an explicit "Never" clause regarding Light Mode. The agent is instructed that the rotating neon beam (`spin-neon`) **MUST NOT** exist, trigger, or be conditionally rendered as invisible in Light Mode. In Light Mode, cards must fall back to a clean, solid white background. Upon user hover, standard cards must display a solid border matching their identity token (e.g., `border-[#10B981]`), while the Sofi AI card maintains its deep purple logic via a solid purple hover border. Nothing can look cluttered; spacing must stay spacious (`p-6` or `space-y-4`).

### The Immutable 3D SOFI Entity Definition (Hyperrealistic Hybrid Blueprint)
The SOFI entity (Intelligence Fiscale) serves as the core AI assistant and core platform differentiator. Transitioning away from primitive flat or SVG concepts, SOFI must be orchestrated by the agent as a high-fidelity, WebGL-rendered 3D entity embedded inside a WebGL Canvas container using library architectures such as `@react-three/fiber`, `three.js`, or fully loaded `Spline` runtime scenes. The agent is explicitly commanded to enforce, instantiate, and protect the following hyperrealistic hybrid visual anatomy and PBR (Physically Based Rendering) material behaviors:

#### 1. Hyperrealistic Hybrid Visual Anatomy
*   **The Frontal Facial Half (Human Core):** The front-facing hemisphere of the head must represent a premium, mature, and highly serious female corporate tax specialist. The facial skin must utilize advanced PBR sub-surface scattering shaders to project ultra-realistic porcelain texture nodes, micro-pores, and crisp skin illumination matching real-world studio lighting. Her expression must remain highly focused and serious, displaying only a microscopic, confident curl at the edges of the lips to communicate absolute financial authority. Her hair is dark, tightly and professionally pinned back in an executive style, providing a clean boundary at the seam.
*   **The Rear Chassis & Infrastructure (Android Core):** The posterior half of the head, the neck articulation collars, and the main shoulder mantle transition into a high-end robotic chassis. The mechanical plates must be rendered with an ultra-glossy polished white ceramic coating (`#FFFFFF`) featuring high clearcoat and low roughness coefficients. The underlying structural bone skeleton, joints, and internal mechanical actuators must utilize a sandblasted matte black titanium compound texture (`#000000`) with high roughness and true metallic reflections.
*   **The Transition Seam:** The boundary separating human tissue shaders from the polished ceramic plates must be a razor-sharp, micro-milled geometric line. Embedded within this microscopic seam, a series of sub-surface emissive channels must glow with a continuous, vibrant Emerald Green line (`#00D4B2`), utilizing high bloom post-processing filters to visualize the data energy flowing through her processing units.

#### 2. The Sacred Brand Core (Torso Logo Integration)
*   **The Sapphire Glass Bay:** Centered directly within the white ceramic chest mantle plate, the agent must render a deeply recessed, circular technological bay. This alcove is hermetically sealed behind a curved, anti-reflective 3D PBR Sapphire Glass lens element.
*   **The Suspended Identity:** Inside the dark carbon-fiber lining of the chest alcove, the brand asset `logo_3.png` must be physically modeled or mapped as a suspended, three-dimensional physical emblem. The structural components of the logo—the Central Star, the Upper-Right Plus Sign, and the Bottom-Left Open Circle—must not be flat textures; they are floating glowing fixtures. They must utilize an emissive light profile that executes a low-frequency, sutil breathing pulse tied to the system’s primary emerald tone (`#00D4B2`), representing SOFI's active computing core.

#### 3. Programmatic Interactivity, Scene Rigging, and State Synchronicity
The agent is fully responsible for rigging the 3D entity container to react dynamically to user input and platform states by updating the material properties and rotation matrices via code:
*   **Cursor Tracking Interaction:** The head and neck joint rotation matrices must listen to screen mouse coordinates, executing a soft, lerp-interpolated `lookAt` tracking animation. To prevent unnatural clipping or mechanical breaking, strict limits must be hardcoded into the rotation bounds, locking horizontal and vertical neck panning to a maximum window of plus/minus 15 degrees.
*   **State-Driven Material Shifting:** The agent must tie the post-processing and emissive intensity layers directly to platform activity hooks. During an idle state, the chest core and seam filaments must perform a smooth breathing frequency. When the `Scanner IA (Factures)` or backend document parsing engines trigger an active request, the green seam lighting and her internal chassis micro-LEDs must transition into an accelerated, calculation-frequency pulse pattern to provide real-time visual processing feedback.

## Tax Form Orchestration and Agent Skills
The financial reporting capabilities of AutoCompt require the accurate management and calculation of highly complex real estate taxation documents. Specifically, the system must handle the federal T776 form (Statement of Real Estate Rentals) for the Canada Revenue Agency, and the provincial TP-128 form (Income and Expenses from Rentals) for Revenu Québec. Both filings are mandatory, and while they share overlapping data points, their calculation rules and depreciation parameters diverge significantly.

Because the intricate mathematical rules governing these forms—such as the specific algorithms for restricting Capital Cost Allowance (CCA) claims to the total net rental income to prevent the creation of artificial losses—exceed the standard contextual reasoning capabilities of an unspecialized LLM, they must be isolated and implemented as distinct Antigravity Skills.

### Designing the Tax Processing Skill
To execute this, a dedicated skill directory (e.g., .agents/skills/tax-form-generator/) must be created within the workspace. The SKILL.md file within this directory defines the YAML frontmatter that allows the agent to discover the skill, alongside the detailed execution logic. By offloading this dense, procedural logic into a specific skill, the agent does not suffer from "Tool Bloat" during normal operations. It loads the heavy CCA calculation parameters and provincial form mappings only when the user explicitly requests the generation or debugging of the financial reporting components.

The skill architecture must explicitly outline several constraints. First, the agent must segregate federal calculation logic from provincial logic, ensuring that variables do not inadvertently cross-contaminate. It must account for specific Quebec rules regarding the TP-128-V supplementary forms. Second, regarding CCA Optimization Rules, the agent must be instructed to programmatically calculate the maximum allowable deduction, but restrict claims so that they never reduce the net rental income below zero. The skill must provide the agent with the exact formulas required to calculate the personal use portion of rental expenses based on inputted percentages. Finally, the skill must assist the agent in calculating and formatting the necessary tax reporting metrics so they can be seamlessly injected into the PDF generation utilities managed by the dataService.ts.

## Legal Compliance and Data Privacy (Loi 16 and Loi 25)
Operating a SaaS platform within the Quebec real estate sector subjects AutoCompt to profound and strictly enforced regulatory frameworks. The AI agent must be fundamentally constrained to never generate code, database schemas, or UI components that violate these provincial laws. Achieving this requires baking legal compliance directly into the agent's DNA via specialized rules and verification loops.

### Ensuring Loi 16 Compliance Architecture
Loi 16 is a sweeping reform that mandates that all co-ownership syndicates establish and maintain a detailed maintenance log (carnet d'entretien) and conduct a comprehensive contingency fund study (étude du fonds de prévoyance). The compliance deadline requires all qualifying buildings to have this documentation verified and produced by August 14, 2028.

When the Antigravity agent interacts with the SyndicLoi16View.tsx component or its underlying Firebase data structures, it must operate under a strict, non-negotiable Skill definition. A specific Antigravity Skill (e.g., loi16-compliance-generator) should be built to format data exactly according to the legislative requirements set out by the provincial government. Crucially, the agent must be forbidden from building standard CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) interfaces for this module. The law requires historical traceability. Therefore, the logic generated must ensure that any entry into the maintenance log is appended, cryptographically timestamped, and rendered immutable, mimicking a secure ledger architecture. The agent must never allow users to easily delete historical maintenance records, as these are legally required artifacts that must survive property management transitions.

### Engineering Loi 25 Data Privacy Guardrails
Loi 25 represents a massive modernization of Quebec's privacy laws, bringing stringent obligations regarding the protection of personal information and aligning the province closer to GDPR standards. Noncompliance with these data protection mandates can result in severe administrative penalties up to $10 million or devastating penal fines reaching up to $25 million (or 4% of worldwide turnover). It is imperative that the AI coding assistant does not introduce architectural vulnerabilities that violate these statutes.

To enforce this, the Antigravity configuration must include a dedicated, high-priority security rule file (e.g., .agents/rules/03-security-loi25.md) acting as the ultimate authority on data handling within the application.

* **Consent and Transparency Defaults:** The rule must dictate that any new form, onboarding flow, or data collection module generated by the AI agent must mathematically default to maximum privacy settings. The agent must be explicitly instructed to automatically include clear, granular consent checkboxes for data collection, strictly avoiding the generation of broad, pre-checked, or buried consent statements.
* **Privacy Impact Assessments (PIA):** Under Loi 25 regulations, PIAs are mandatory when developing, acquiring, or significantly overhauling systems that handle personal data. To manage this, a specific Antigravity workflow (/generate-pia) must be created. Before the agent is permitted to commit any significant architectural changes to the Firebase data models or authentication flows, the workflow forces the agent to pause execution, analyze its proposed changes, and generate a comprehensive Markdown PIA document assessing data sensitivity, external transfer risks, and implemented safeguards. A human developer must review and approve this document before the code can be merged.
* **Data Anonymization and Deletion Protocols:** Loi 25 grants individuals enhanced rights, including the right to have their personal data erased or irrevocably anonymized when it is no longer required. The agent must be instructed to build sophisticated soft-delete mechanisms and robust data masking utilities within the dataService.ts. The Antigravity rule must state: "Never generate raw SQL or NoSQL queries that permanently delete user records from the database without first checking for a legal retention hold. Prioritize cryptographic anonymization processes over raw data deletion to maintain relational integrity in financial ledgers while satisfying privacy requests."

## Safe Refactoring Strategies for the Monolithic Architecture
The most critical and immediate architectural vulnerability identified in the current state of the AutoCompt application is the massive App.tsx file. At an overwhelming 23,573 lines, this single React component functions as an unstable monolith containing complex routing logic, expansive global state management, and dense UI rendering instructions. From an engineering perspective, it is highly unmaintainable. Furthermore, from an AI governance perspective, an unconstrained AI agent attempting to optimize or refactor a file of this magnitude is almost guaranteed to cause catastrophic systemic failure due to standard LLM context-window degradation and the loss of complex variable scoping over thousands of lines.

To safely execute the necessary decoupling of this monolith without destroying the existing functionality, a rigorous, fully automated verification loop must be established utilizing sequential Antigravity Workflows.

### The Refactoring Workflow Protocol
A global workflow (e.g., /refactor-monolith) must be defined using YAML within the .agents/workflows/ directory. This workflow dictates a methodical, step-by-step extraction process that strips the agent of its autonomy to make sweeping, multi-file changes without verification:

1.  **Strict Branch Isolation:** The workflow must begin by forcing the agent to isolate its workspace. It must utilize the Antigravity /fork command to spin up a duplicate parallel session, or execute the gh CLI to initialize a new, isolated Git feature branch. The agent is explicitly and permanently forbidden from committing structural changes directly to the main production branch.
2.  **Architectural Parsing and Audit:** The agent must execute a deep semantic scan and Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) analysis of the App.tsx monolith to identify isolated logical domains. For example, it must map the dependencies of the Bureau à domicile logic, isolating its specific state hooks, utility imports, and JSX returns, preparing it to be extracted into a standalone component as noted in the pending tasks.
3.  **The Test-and-Tea Loop (Pre-Extraction Verification):** This is the most vital step in the protocol. Antigravity requires verification to ensure correct modifications. Because the AutoCompt project currently completely lacks unit tests, the workflow must be programmed to instruct the agent to first write a standard test block (using a framework like Vitest or Jest) for the exact logic it intends to extract, before making any modifications to the App.tsx file itself.
4.  **Component Extraction and Execution:** Once a baseline test is established and passes against the monolith, the agent extracts the identified logic into a distinct, modular .tsx file within the src/components/ directory, updating the routing imports in App.tsx.
5.  **Browser Verification via Sub-Agents:** Antigravity possesses a unique, highly advanced capability to dispatch a headless browser sub-agent to navigate the local web application. The workflow must instruct the agent to utilize this browser-verifier skill. The sub-agent boots the Vite development server, navigates to the newly decoupled UI element, clicks through the interface flows, and captures state-based artifacts (such as screenshots or short video recordings) to prove that the visual UX integrity and state management remain perfectly intact.
6.  **The Human Review Gate:** Finally, the agent halts its autonomous execution and requests mandatory human review. By configuring the workspace settings to request-review or utilizing the strict mode in the settings.json, the developer is presented with the test results, the browser verification artifacts, and the code diffs for final approval before the branch can be merged.

By utilizing this rigidly structured workflow, the 23,573-line monolith can be systematically dismantled into maintainable, highly cohesive modules over a series of controlled iterations, entirely without violating the primary Golden Rule of non-deletion, as the original logic is meticulously ported, tested, visually verified, and preserved in the modernized architecture.

## Securing API Integrations and Addressing the Incomplete Roadmap
The application state summary indicates that the platform is approximately 75% complete. While the core infrastructure, authentication, and primary Syndicat modules are functional, several critical security vulnerabilities and incomplete features remain. The most pressing issue is the exposure of API keys. The GOOGLE_API_KEY and GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID are currently hardcoded directly within the App.tsx file, and the GEMINI_API_KEY requires secure configuration for the Vercel production environment.

### Enforcing Strict Environment Variable Discipline
To resolve this critical vulnerability and prevent future occurrences, the Antigravity agent must be constrained by an Always On security rule that actively hunts for exposed credentials across the repository. This rule must enforce strict "Environment Variable Discipline":

* **Continuous Pattern Recognition:** The agent must be instructed to continuously scan its working context for standard credential storage patterns, such as apiKey = "...", client_secret, or exposed Firebase configuration strings. Upon detection, the agent must autonomously halt its primary task and refactor the exposed strings to utilize secure environment variables (e.g., process.env.VITE_GOOGLE_API_KEY or Vite's standard import.meta.env architecture).
* **Documentation Blacklisting:** The AI agent must be explicitly forbidden from documenting actual API key values, passwords, or sensitive connection strings in the project's README, .agents/skills/ documentation, or any other plain-text file committed to version control.
* **Execution Containment Rings:** To prevent the agent from inadvertently leaking keys through terminal commands during debugging processes, terminal executions should be restricted to a secure sandbox containment ring. By configuring the Antigravity CLI settings to proceed-in-sandbox, the system ensures that while the agent can autonomously format code and run isolated local tests, any external network calls, remote curl commands, or risky shell executions require explicit manual review and authorization.

### Finalizing the Feature Roadmap via Agent Orchestration
With the security boundaries and UI constraints firmly established, the Antigravity agent can be safely deployed to complete the remaining 25% of the AutoCompt roadmap. The pending tasks require varied approaches:

* **Kilométrage GPS & Facturation:** These modules are currently referenced in the RBAC matrix for the Prospecteur and Flippeur profiles but lack dedicated components. The agent can utilize a standard generation workflow to scaffold these views, bounded by the strict UI/UX visual constraints, ensuring they match the existing glassmorphism aesthetic without requiring manual styling adjustments.
* **Google Drive OAuth per Workspace:** The infrastructure exists within driveService.ts, but the multi-tenant Phase 2 flow is not active. The agent must construct the authentication handshakes required to generate distinct OAuth tokens for different enterprise workspaces, utilizing the previously established multi-tenant folder architecture rules.
* **Conciliation Bancaire:** While basic functionality is present, true integration requires connecting to external banking data. The agent must be guided to build secure middleware proxies within the Express server (server.ts) to handle Plaid or Flinks API interactions, rather than attempting to securely process bank feeds directly on the client side.

## Conclusion: Achieving Deterministic Autonomy
The successful transition of the AutoCompt SaaS platform from a structurally precarious, human-authored monolith into a highly secure, agile, and agent-augmented ecosystem relies entirely on the precise and uncompromising configuration of the Google Antigravity governance framework. By shifting the engineering paradigm away from reactive prompt engineering and toward the establishment of immutable workspace rules, structured operational workflows, and progressive agent skills, development teams can harness the unprecedented velocity of artificial intelligence while completely mitigating the severe risks of code destruction, architectural degradation, or security exposure.

The encoding of the designated "Golden Rules" as persistent, high-priority system constraints guarantees that the fundamental mechanisms of the application—such as the core Google Drive database integration and the non-destructive, profile-based conditional rendering of React modules—remain permanently secure against AI hallucination. The deployment of Glob-targeted rules ensures absolute, pixel-perfect fidelity to the specified UI/UX directives, protecting the complex CSS implementations of the dual-mode glassmorphism cards and the critical intellectual property encapsulated within the SOFI entity branding.

Furthermore, by comprehensively translating stringent regional legal requirements, such as the Loi 16 property maintenance statutes and the Loi 25 privacy mandates, into deterministic AI guardrails, the system guarantees that rapid feature development never compromises the platform's legal standing. Similarly, encapsulating complex tax calculation protocols (TPS/TVQ tracking and T776/TP-128 CCA limits) into isolated agent skills prevents the AI from becoming overwhelmed by irrelevant context during routine operations. Ultimately, this exhaustive, multi-layered governance strategy transforms the AI coding assistant from a highly unpredictable and risky variable into a highly controlled, deterministic engineering engine, capable of safely dismantling legacy technical debt while continuously and autonomously adhering to the exact operational, visual, and legal parameters defined by the AutoCompt architecture.